173	Inclusive Dump Closure Processes in Brazil	Technical Resource	\N	Brazils National Solid Waste Policy mandates that all open air dumps in the country must close. In this technical paper the reports (The Closure of Gramacho and Relatorio Projeto Reciclando Oportunidades: Gerando Trabalho e Renda, Manhuau) of two specific dump closure processes in Brazil are reviewed. Besides a summary of the two reports an overview of their shared methodological approaches and key takeaways is described. The unique achievements and challenges brought about by distinct circumstances of the dump closures are also discussed in this technical report.	\N	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/resource_173.png	national	[]	\N	2021-04-28 06:24:39.738788+00	2021-06-10 08:52:26.738571+00	76	\N	\N	\N	\N	APPROVED	\N	\N	\N
252	Strategic Plan For Monitoring And Evaluation Of Garbage In The Sea Of The State OfSo Paulo (PEMALM)	Technical Resource	\N	Coastal and marine environments are important providers of ecosystem services, among which  is the regulation of our planets climate. In Brazil, some of the largest cities of the country are found  along the coastline, concentrating intense economic activity that relies on, impacts, and shares space  with a rich, though vulnerable, biodiversity. Recognizing this dynamic is fundamental to think, plan  and act to guarantee a viable future. For FUNBIO, the support to projects aiming for ocean knowledge  and conservation has always been a priority. And it is with great satisfaction that we take part in the  initiative that has generated the present So Paulo Strategic Plan for Monitoring and Assessment  of Marine Litter (PEMALM), a partnership involving the University of So Paulo, the Norwegian  Embassy and the Secretariat of Infrastructure and Environment of the State of So Paulo. Since the early days of its activities, in 1996, FUNBIO has supported the creation and  strengthening of marine and coastal protected areas. This also extends to studies about species, coastal  and marine environments, and fishery resources. The plan represents an important step towards the  creation of an information database in the state of So Paulo, which can subsidize future means to  combat marine litter. A global and growing challenge that requires equally global, and ever-increasing,  knowledge and effort from all of society for mitigation.	\N	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/resource_252.png	\N	["https://drive.google.com/file/d/1GFXQIJjEZ0dRwfeXzun1EoKHP-D8PVMU/view"]	\N	2021-04-28 06:24:40.745362+00	2021-06-10 08:52:26.738571+00	76	\N	\N	\N	\N	APPROVED	\N	\N	\N
91	Marine Litter Prevention	Technical Resource	\N	This study deals with the question of how decision-makers can improve their municipal solid waste management systems and move towards a circular economy in order to prevent plastic leakage into waterways and the ocean. It focuses on plastic waste from human settlements as a substantial share of marine litter consists of plastics stemming from land-based sources. A methodological approach is elaborated to assess plastic waste leakage in qualitative and quantitative terms, enabling deeper understanding of these characteristically chaotic plastic waste flows. 10 KEY MESSAGES FOR PREVENTING MARINE LITTER 1. Promote integrated sustainable waste management 2. Respect the waste hierarchy: reduce, reuse, recycle as much as possible 3. Drastically expand waste collection coverage, efficiency and the separation of plastics 4. Enhance awareness raising and cleaning activities of streets, canals and beaches 5. Build sound institutions, policies, operator models and cost-recovery mechanisms 6. Implement extended producer responsibility schemes and deposit-refund systems 7. Promote reusable packaging and product design for recycling 8. Enable cooperation of stakeholders across sectors from source to sea 9. Facilitate the exchange of local decision-makers across borders 10. Strengthen dialogue along plastic and packaging value chains	\N	\N	transnational	[]	\N	2021-04-28 06:24:37.639123+00	2021-06-10 08:52:26.849414+00	276	\N	\N	\N	\N	APPROVED	\N	\N	\N
136	PlasticBudget: Accounting of plastics in the environment	Technical Resource	\N	In order to take political action, it is important to know the sources, quantities, and distribution of plastics in the environment. The findings should be used to derive a per capita budget for plastics that defines the maximum ecologically compatible quantity of emissions per person. In addition, methods are being developed to adequately reflect the potential effects of macro- and microplastic emissions in eco-assessments. The project results create a quantitative basis for future political decision-making processes. The PlasticBudget project is therefore divided into two parts: 1) Development of a budget approach that can be used to determine the permissible global total quantities in water bodies and the annual per capita emissions of plastics into the environment. 2) Development of an impact assessment methodology with corresponding environmental indicators in order to consider the plastic waste problem in environmental auditing. Similar to the balance calculation for greenhouse gases in the climate problem, reference variables such as plastic equivalents are developed as a basis for decision-making.	\N	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/resource_136.png	\N	[]	\N	2021-04-28 06:24:38.98057+00	2021-06-10 08:52:26.849414+00	276	\N	\N	\N	\N	APPROVED	\N	\N	\N
