nels.NAVIGATION SUBSYSTEM FREDs hulls are propelled forward using electrical motors which receive electricity from the solar panel/battery assembly. Propulsion by the motors can be made autonomous or performed via remote control.SENSOR SUBSYSTEM FREDs architecture provides a platform for embedding scientific sensors and instrumentation to be used for collecting data and samples from the environment. Some sensors provide performance information, such as FREDs speed and location, and other sensors capture weather data, such as air and water temperature, wind speed, and current strength. FREDs sensors are powered by solar energy.DATA COMMUNICATIONS SUBSYSTEMWhile FRED is in marine environments, its data communications capability enables commands to be transmitted from ground control to FRED and operational data to be transmitted from FRED to ground control. This enables remote control, navigational routes, and display of FRED operational data. Our 50-foot FRED is designed to deliver the following enhanced capabilities per our system requirements baseline:\tCollect floating marine plastic and debris ranging in size from 5mm to 5 meters on a 24/7 basis\tPropel at 2 knots to prevent unannounced infringement on marine life\tNavigate autonomously based on GPS trajectory commands from mission control staff\tNavigate under remote control during unsafe conditions (storms, etc.)\tUtilize only solar power for FRED operations with stored energy available on cloudy days  \tProvide excess stored energy to governmental and commercial marine Underwater Autonomous Vehicles (UAVs) for recharging their batteries without having to return to land\tAlert marine mammals of FRED proximity using appropriate acoustic pingers recommended by marine scientists at Scripps Institute of Oceanography\tCapture environmental, oceanographic, and marine ecosystem data in real-time for transmittal to designated scientific, governmental, and commercial information systems\tTransmit sensor and instrumentati